GLANCE.full_title: Performance of the ATLAS Trigger System in 2010

GLANCE.label: Performances of the Atlas jet trigger

abstract.summary: This note summarises the performance of the electron and photon triggers during the ATLAS data taking in 2010. Approximately 45 pb^{-1} of proton-proton collision data at a centre of mass energy of sqrt(s)= 7 TeV were collected under stable beam conditions. In the initial commissioning phase the event selection was based only on the first level trigger. The high-level trigger was run but without rejecting any events. With increasing luminosities the high-level trigger was progressively put in to rejection mode. Since August, when a liminosity of ~10^{31} cm^{-2} {s}^{-1} was reached, all triggers have relied on the HLT selection. In this note results from the commissioning phase as well as first results of the physics performance will be shown. Comparisons of selection variables, based on calorimeter and tracking information calculated by the different trigger levels, with the offline reconstruction will be shown. This has been an important step in the commissioning of these triggers to ensure their correct functioning. Electrons from physics signals such as J/Psi->ee, W->enu, Z->ee have been used to extract the trigger efficiencies with respect to the offline benchmark selections. HLT efficiencies are typically of the order of 99%, and are higher for offline electrons and photons with transverse energies above the turn-on region.

title.title: Performance of the Electron and Photon Trigger in p-p Collisions at sqrt(s) = 7 TeV

abstract.summary: Proton-proton collisions at $\sqrt{s}=7$ TeV and heavy ion collisions at $\sqrt{s_{NN}}$=2.76 TeV were produced by the LHC and recorded using the ATLAS experiment's trigger system in 2010. The LHC is designed with a maximum bunch crossing rate of 40 MHz and the ATLAS trigger system is designed to record approximately 200 of these per second. The trigger system selects events by rapidly identifying signatures of muon, electron, photon, tau lepton, jet, and B meson candidates, as well as using global event signatures, such as missing transverse energy. An overview of the ATLAS trigger system, the evolution of the system during 2010 and the performance of the trigger system components and selections based on the 2010 collision data are shown. A brief outline of plans for the trigger system in 2011 is presented

title.title: Performance of the ATLAS Trigger System in 2010

authors.full_name: Goncalves Pinto Firmino Da Costa, Joao
